<tr class="\&quot;textDragger\&quot;" tabindex="\&quot;5a3ba790423b20f8d09f117c\&quot;" data-column="\&quot;column-text-layout\&quot;">
<td>
<table class="\&quot;draggable-item" border="\&quot;0\&quot;" width="\&quot;600\&quot;" cellspacing="\&quot;0\&quot;" cellpadding="\&quot;0\&quot;" align="\&quot;center\&quot;">

<tr>
<td class="\&quot;rLvE\&quot;">
<div class="\&quot;templateSettings\&quot;">&nbsp;</div>

<div class="\&quot;text-resizer">
<div class="\&quot;ui-widget-text" role="\&quot;textbox\&quot;" contenteditable="\&quot;true\&quot;" spellcheck="\&quot;true\&quot;" data-medium-editor-element="\&quot;true\&quot;" aria-multiline="\&quot;true\&quot;" data-placeholder="\&quot;Type">
<p class="\&quot;heading-style8\&quot;">Definitions and guidelines</p>
<p><span class="\&quot;heading-style9">Homogenous</span> Loading</p>
<p>Loading the ship with a full single grade cargo at or near her full load draft or with all holds being full within the allowable load capacities of each holds.</p>
<p class="\&quot;heading-style9\&quot;">Alternate hold (or Jump) loading</p>
<p>Loading the ship with a full cargo at or near her full load draft, using only the odd numbered holds or as per loading manual.</p>
<p>Comply with any restrictions imposed within the loading manual or by the administration.</p>
<p>Apply the bulkhead correction factor to the sheering force to keep it within maximum limits.</p>
<p class="\&quot;heading-style9\&quot;">Block Loading</p>
<p>Loading 2 or more adjacent holds and one or more holds in between being empty.</p>
<p>Comply with loading manual for block loading condition. Contact Marine Superintendent if conditions given in loading manual are not satisfied.</p>
<p class="\&quot;heading-style9\&quot;">Hazardous Cargo Loading</p>
<p>Load bulk cargo which has liquefaction or chemical hazards only if the ship is certified to carry the same.</p>
<p>Comply with the limits for transport such as T.M.L., maximum concentrations, etc mentioned in the IMSBC code.</p>
<p>Comply with the requirements of the IMDG code where applicable.</p>
<p class="\&quot;heading-style9\&quot;">Grain</p>
<p>The term grain covers wheat, maize (corn), oats, rye, barley, rice, pulses, seeds and processed form thereof, whose behaviour is similar to that of grain in its natural state. Grain cargoes possess the characteristics of low cohesive strength and with low angle of repose.</p>
<p>Comply with the requirements of the IMO grain code and shipï¿½s grain loading manual.</p>
<p>Ensure that the Document of Authorisation for loading grain is available on board.</p>
<p class="\&quot;heading-style9\&quot;">Single pass loading</p>
<p>Loading of cargo with only one pour per hold, normally applicable to VLOC designed and approved for the same.</p>
<p class="\&quot;heading-style9\&quot;">Flow Moisture Point (FMP)</p>
<p>The maximum water content, expressed as a percentage, at which a sample of cargo will begin to lose shear strength. Cargoes with moisture content beyond FMP may be liable liquefy.</p>
<p>Transportable Moisture Limit (TML) is defined as 90% of the FMP.&nbsp;</p>

<tbody>
<tr class="\&quot;textDragger\&quot;" tabindex="\&quot;5a3ba6527f9df85b4f70d1a8\&quot;" data-column="\&quot;column-text-layout\&quot;">
<td>
<table class="\&quot;draggable-item" border="\&quot;0\&quot;" width="\&quot;600\&quot;" cellspacing="\&quot;0\&quot;" cellpadding="\&quot;0\&quot;" align="\&quot;center\&quot;">
<tbody>
<tr>
<td class="\&quot;rLvE\&quot;">
<div class="\&quot;templateSettings\&quot;">&nbsp;</div>
<div class="\&quot;drg-rmv-settings-copy\&quot;">&nbsp;</div>
<div class="\&quot;text-resizer">
<div class="\&quot;ui-widget-text" role="\&quot;textbox\&quot;" contenteditable="\&quot;true\&quot;" spellcheck="\&quot;true\&quot;" data-medium-editor-element="\&quot;true\&quot;" aria-multiline="\&quot;true\&quot;" data-placeholder="\&quot;Type">
<p class="\&quot;heading-style8\&quot;">Inspection and maintenance</p>
<p>Causes of damage to the side shell are:</p>
<ul id="\&quot;5a3ba675ef750fd9ea0fe7e1\&quot;" class="\&quot;ul-box" tabindex="\&quot;5a3ba675b98aabe7378606bb\&quot;" data-id="\&quot;NaN\&quot;">
<li>By contact with jetty, tugs, barges and lock walls</li>
<li>From impact by grabs, cargo dislodging equipment like bulldozers and strikers during discharge</li>
<li>Corrosion through chemical action from certain cargoes</li>
<li>Fatigue failure</li>
<li>Sloshing effect due to partially filled spaces</li>
<li>Damage to bow plating through impacts associated with swinging or loosely stowed anchors</li>
</ul>
<p>Inspect and maintain the ship and equipment as per Company PMS.</p>
<p>Check the following before the commencement of cargo operations:</p>
<ul id="\&quot;5a3ba67bc0520d7b28ee3fab\&quot;" class="\&quot;ul-box" tabindex="\&quot;5a3ba67b2875f8aeefc89d4b\&quot;" data-id="\&quot;NaN\&quot;">
<li>Hatch covers including hatch track ways and compression bars</li>
<li>Cross wedges</li>
<li>Side cleats and centre Bolts</li>
<li>Cargo holds</li>
<li>Ventilation arrangements</li>
<li>Tank tops</li>
<li>Hold framing</li>
<li>Operational readiness of all safety equipment</li>
<li>Sounding pipes and air pipes</li>
<li>Derricks / Cranes</li>
<li>Standing and running rigging with fixtures</li>
<li>Lashing points</li>
<li>All other cargo gear</li>
</ul>
<p class="\&quot;heading-style9\&quot;">Hatch Covers</p>
<p>Test hatch covers for weather tightness by hose test, chalk test or ultrasonic testing. Carry out testing before each loading or at three [3] monthly intervals and record the results in the Deck Logbook.</p>
<p>Follow the PMS to ensure that:</p>
<ul id="\&quot;5a3ba67fe49be842b23cd4e0\&quot;" class="\&quot;ul-box" tabindex="\&quot;5a3ba67f6a3df64d9f9fa7e3\&quot;" data-id="\&quot;NaN\&quot;">
<li>The steel is not allowed to corrode</li>
<li>Gaskets are replaced when required</li>
<li>Movable parts are kept properly lubricated</li>
<li>Fittings are overhauled</li>
</ul>
<p>Monitor closely the condition at the peripheral and cross-joint gaskets especially for:</p>
<ul id="\&quot;5a3ba68249efc033d8c36d20\&quot;" class="\&quot;ul-box" tabindex="\&quot;5a3ba682e400777148608224\&quot;" data-id="\&quot;NaN\&quot;">
<li>Rubber</li>
<li>Compression bars</li>
<li>Locking devices</li>
<li>Cleats</li>
<li>Load bearing surfaces</li>
<li>General condition of the coaming edge</li>
</ul>
<p class="\&quot;\&quot;">Follow manufacturerï¿½s maintenance procedures where the hatch panels are moved by hydraulic means.</p>
<p>Ensure that the covers remain closed and weather tight in the event of hydraulic failure, where hydraulic cleats or securing arrangements exist.</p>
<p>Comply with the manufacturer's instructions for the safe operation, inspection, maintenance and repair for the type of hatch cover fitted on the ship.</p>
<p class="\&quot;heading-style9\&quot;">Cargo Hold</p>
<p>Hammer test to check for loose or corroded parts on access ladders.</p>
<p>Carry out random thickness measurements where possible to establish the level of diminution, if coatings have broken down.</p>
<p>De-rust and paint prior to loading depending on requirements of the next cargo, time permitting</p>
<p>Closely inspect the boundaries of corrugations and bulkhead stools, particularly in way of shelf plates, shedder plates, deck, inner bottom, etc., where fractures usually occur.</p>
<p>Inspect stool spaces and other void spaces for any ingress of water. Take great care when opening manholes or drain plugs to stool spaces when sounding indicate the presence of water, as the space[s] may be pressurized.</p>
<p>Clean and inspect the bilge wells closely as heavy pitting corrosion may have occurred due to accumulated water/corrosive solution in the wells. Pay special attention to the plating in way of the bilge suction and sounding pipes.</p>
<p>Visually inspect the general corrosion condition of the tank top structure.</p>
<p>Pay special attention to areas where pipes penetrate the tank top.</p>
<p>Inspect double bottom tanks whenever deformations are observed on the tank top to determine the extent of the damage.</p>
<p>Inspect carefully all ballast or bunker tank sounding and air pipes which pass through the cargo holds.</p>
<p>Inspect regularly any hold bilge sounding pipes which pass through ballast tanks.</p>
<p>Check all tank manholes for physical integrity and water tightness.</p>
<p class="\&quot;heading-style9\&quot;">Ballast holds</p>
<p>Always maintain all associated equipment such as valves, strainers and port hold blanks in working condition.</p>
<p>Inspect bilge blanks after carefully fitting them and monitor any leakage past the blank.</p>
<p>Pressure test the sumps after discharge of ballast.</p>
<p class="\&quot;heading-style9\&quot;">Ballast Tanks and Void Spaces</p>
<p>Carry out ballast tank and void space inspections as per the Company PMS and additional inspection as required.&nbsp;</p>
</div>

<p class="\&quot;heading-style8\&quot;">Ballast operations</p>
<p>Avoid ballasting in ports or rivers especially where low under keel clearance is expected, or where waters are excessively muddy.</p>
<p>Monitor cargo holds for leaks when taking in ballast during discharging operations.</p>
<p class="\&quot;heading-style9\&quot;">Heavy Weather Ballast (HWB)</p>
<p>Take Heavy Weather Ballast to achieve the following if adverse weather is expected:</p>
<ul id="\&quot;5a3ba51fca3cd106027b36e7\&quot;" class="\&quot;ul-box" tabindex="\&quot;5a3ba51f49f359473a2161de\&quot;" data-id="\&quot;NaN\&quot;">
<li>Reduce stresses on the hull of the ship</li>
<li>Provide for transverse stability</li>
<li>Aid propulsion by controlling the submergence of the propeller</li>
<li>Aid manoeuvrability by submerging the rudder and reducing the amount of exposed hull surface</li>
<li>Compensate for weight lost from fuel and water consumption</li>
</ul>
</div>
</div>
</td>
</tr>
</tbody>
</table>
</td>
</tr>

<p>Inform Technical Superintendent when chlorination of ballast water is required by port authorities. Put a remark on invoices for chlorination stating ï¿½compulsory by port authority ordersï¿½.</p>
<p class="\&quot;heading-style9\&quot;">VLOC Ballast Operation</p>
<p>Monitor the pumps, valves, ballast lines, leak gauges in the engine room during ballast operations.</p>
<p>Ensure the oil level is sufficient in the power-pack for operating hydraulic valves before ballast operation.</p>
<p>Ensure sufficient reserve hydraulic oil for power pack is available on board.</p>
<p>Test valve operation from the local solenoid and with the portable hydraulic pump. Train the crew in the use of this pump.</p>
<p>Keep the door of the duct keel to the engine room open. Take frequent rounds of the duct keel to check for possible seawater leaks from ballast line dresser couplings and hydraulic valves.</p>
</div>

<p>Secure covers in position when hatch covers are open for hold cleaning at sea.</p>

<p>Following are generally the varying standards of cleaning that may be required:</p>

<li>Washed down followed by freshwater rinse</li>
<li>Grain Standard</li>
<li>Excess of grain standard such as for soda ash</li>
<li>ï¿½Hospital cleanï¿½ for fertilisers bound for Australia</li>
<li>Additional measures e.g. salt in bulk may require the application of lime wash</li>
<li>Application of special coating e.g. hold block, slip coat, etc.</li>

<p class="\&quot;heading-style8\&quot;">Water Ingress Alarm System (WIAS)</p>
<p>Be familiar with manufacturerï¿½s instructions, drawings for the WIAS system, testing of and location of sensors.</p>
<p>Disable the WIAS sensor prior taking ballast into that hold.</p>
<p>Test the sensors in cargo holds and other spaces manually or by simulation using sea or fresh water (as recommended by maker) on the sensors individually and confirm the alarm is activated on the Bridge.</p>
<p>Carry out and record these tests before each loading.</p>

<table class="\&quot;draggable-item" border="\&quot;0\&quot;" width="\&quot;600\&quot;" cellspacing="\&quot;0\&quot;" cellpadding="\&quot;0\&quot;" align="\&quot;center\&quot;">

<div class="\&quot;ui-widget-text" role="\&quot;textbox\&quot;" contenteditable="\&quot;true\&quot;" spellcheck="\&quot;true\&quot;" data-medium-editor-element="\&quot;true\&quot;" aria-multiline="\&quot;true\&quot;" data-placeholder="\&quot;Type">
<p class="\&quot;heading-style8\&quot;">Bilge Operation</p>
<p>Monitor deck crew to ensure no short cuts are taken while bilge cleaning.</p>
<p>Clean all residues from the bilges.</p>
<p>Flush the bilge line after every hold washing to clear the line.</p>
<p>Open and clean all bilge line valves in Engine room including the non-return valves before each loading.</p>
<p>Overhaul the non-return flaps in the hold bilges at intervals not exceeding 6 months and as soon as possible after a ship has been taken into management.</p>
<p>Test the non-return valves (NRV) in the bilge suction lines to a pressure of 2 to 3 bar while in the open position. Do not exceed 4 bar pressure to avoid damage to the bilge system valves.</p>
<p>Check all hydraulic, pneumatic and solenoid valves including the remote indicators for correct operation. Perform these checks every 3 months for valves which are located in the engine room, duct keel, stool spaces and inside ballast tanks whenever the tanks are entered for inspection.</p>
</div>

<table class="\&quot;draggable-item" border="\&quot;0\&quot;" width="\&quot;600\&quot;" cellspacing="\&quot;0\&quot;" cellpadding="\&quot;0\&quot;" align="\&quot;center\&quot;">

<tr>
<td class="\&quot;rLvE\&quot;">
<div class="\&quot;templateSettings\&quot;">&nbsp;</div>

<div class="\&quot;text-resizer">
<div class="\&quot;ui-widget-text" role="\&quot;textbox\&quot;" contenteditable="\&quot;true\&quot;" spellcheck="\&quot;true\&quot;" data-medium-editor-element="\&quot;true\&quot;" aria-multiline="\&quot;true\&quot;" data-placeholder="\&quot;Type">
<p class="\&quot;heading-style8\&quot;">Cargo Loading</p>
<p>Obtain the Constant from initial draft survey before loading. Try to keep this constant as low as is reasonably practicable.</p>
<p>Inform the Marine Superintendent in case the shore representative is not available or refuses to sign the Ship-Shore safety checklist. Make a suitable remark in the checklist.</p>
<p>Check depths at berth by manual soundings to verify sufficient under keel clearance and for echo sounder accuracy. Suspend loading operations at low water in case required, except where NAABSA clause applies.</p>
<p>Consult the pilot and ensure safe operations before opening hatch covers, when required by terminal before arrival at berth.</p>
<p>Supervise the commencement of each grade to ensure that the correct cargo grade is commenced.</p>
<p>Calculate cargo quantity from draft survey and compare with the shore figure at least every 6 hours and on changeover of grades.</p>
<p>Open hatch covers only partially while preparing ballast holds for loading.</p>
<p class="\&quot;heading-style9\&quot;">\tDeparture</p>
<p>Give sufficient notice to the terminal to clear any spillage on the deck, coamings and hatch covers before departure.</p>
<p>Apply sealing tape to the hatch cover openings if required by charterers, owners or nature of the cargo.</p>
<p>Complete all paperwork and documentation and prepare the ship to leave the berth.</p>
</div>
</div>

<div class="\&quot;text-resizer">
<div class="\&quot;ui-widget-text" role="\&quot;textbox\&quot;" contenteditable="\&quot;true\&quot;" spellcheck="\&quot;true\&quot;" data-medium-editor-element="\&quot;true\&quot;" aria-multiline="\&quot;true\&quot;" data-placeholder="\&quot;Type">
<p class="\&quot;heading-style8\&quot;">Fumigation and Gas Freeing</p>
<p>Set accommodation ventilation flaps to maintain positive pressure within the accommodation spaces during fumigation. Ensure all hold openings are sealed. Check the sealing and air tightness of cable ducts and pipes before fumigation.</p>
<p>Ensure that sufficient gas tubes provided for gas testing. Check the expiry dates.</p>
<p>Carry out gas freeing operations if required by the fumigation plan that has been provided by the charterers or the authorized fumigation company.</p>
<p>Suspend gas freeing if the winds are blowing from the cargo hold towards the accommodation.</p>
<p>Open cargo holds at the discharge port only after testing for gas and wearing the correct PPE including gas masks or SCBA as required.</p>
<p>Aluminium Phosphide tablets</p>
<p class="\&quot;heading-style9\&quot;">Aluminium Phosphide tablets are:</p>
<ul id="\&quot;5a3b83b2125b65f924b21091\&quot;" class="\&quot;ul-box" tabindex="\&quot;5a3b83b215f34ef69e85572b\&quot;" data-id="\&quot;NaN\&quot;">
<li>A common pesticide for grain cargoes</li>
<li>Reacts with moisture in the air and liberates a dangerous gas ï¿½ Phosphine</li>
</ul>
</div>
</div>
</td>
</tr>
</tbody>
</table>
</td>
</tr>
<tr id="\&quot;@bookmarkId\&quot;" class="\&quot;\&quot;" tabindex="\&quot;59cb794d4055231576247e1f\&quot;" data-value="\&quot;59cb794d4055231576247e1f\&quot;" data-column="\&quot;column-WarningBSM-layout\&quot;" data-aria="\&quot;TOC_Support_Control\&quot;">

<div class="\&quot;WarningText\&quot;" contenteditable="\&quot;true\&quot;" spellcheck="\&quot;true\&quot;">Exposure to Phosphine gas may be fatal.</div>

<table class="\&quot;draggable-item" border="\&quot;0\&quot;" width="\&quot;600\&quot;" cellspacing="\&quot;0\&quot;" cellpadding="\&quot;0\&quot;" align="\&quot;center\&quot;">

<td class="\&quot;rLvE\&quot;">
<div class="\&quot;templateSettings\&quot;">&nbsp;</div>

<div class="\&quot;text-resizer">
<div class="\&quot;ui-widget-text" role="\&quot;textbox\&quot;" contenteditable="\&quot;true\&quot;" spellcheck="\&quot;true\&quot;" data-medium-editor-element="\&quot;true\&quot;" aria-multiline="\&quot;true\&quot;" data-placeholder="\&quot;Type">
<p>Phosphine gas:</p>
<ul id="\&quot;5a3b8409761235cb2f97eff9\&quot;" class="\&quot;ul-box" tabindex="\&quot;5a3b8409cab37a38fdef30d7\&quot;" data-id="\&quot;NaN\&quot;">
<li>Kills insects and rodents by decompressing their central nervous system and respiratory function.</li>
<li>Is dangerous to humans and may cause coughing, nausea, headaches, pain and tightness in the chest, shortness of breath, vomiting and convulsions.</li>
<li>Symptoms of lung edema become manifest after a few hours and are aggravated by physical effort.</li>
<li>Is heavier than air (by about a factor of 1.17) but the gas has been known to rise into the accommodation, probably due to over-pressure in the cargo holds.</li>
<li>Has been described as having a fishy smell and sometimes as smelling of garlic.</li>
</ul>
</div>
</div>

<p class="\&quot;heading-style8\&quot;">Cargo Monitoring</p>
<p>Pump out bilges if acidic conditions are indicated during pH test when carrying coal cargo.</p>
<p>Pump out bilges regularly to prevent the accumulation of water in the bilges. Maintain a pumping record and keep charterers advised.</p>
<p>Obtain the following information from Shipper before loading:</p>
<ul id="\&quot;5a3b804258b563385a20767d\&quot;" class="\&quot;ul-box" tabindex="\&quot;5a3b80420a0cab50c9ce84f4\&quot;" data-id="\&quot;NaN\&quot;">
<li>BCSN (Bulk cargo Shipping name)</li>
<li>Shippers declaration as per IMSBC Code including cargo is not HME (Harmful to marine environment)</li>
<li>MSDS for Group-B (Cargoes which possess a chemical hazard) cargoes</li>
<li>Flow Moisture Point (FMP) and Transportable Moisture Limit (TML) for cargoes which may liquefy</li>
<li>Lab test report giving the TML of a representative sample of the cargo to be loaded and its actual moisture content.</li>
</ul>
</div>
</div>
</td>
</tr>
</tbody>
</table>
</td>
</tr>

<table class="\&quot;draggable-item" border="\&quot;0\&quot;" width="\&quot;600\&quot;" cellspacing="\&quot;0\&quot;" cellpadding="\&quot;0\&quot;" align="\&quot;center\&quot;">

<div class="\&quot;ui-widget-text" role="\&quot;textbox\&quot;" contenteditable="\&quot;true\&quot;" spellcheck="\&quot;true\&quot;" data-medium-editor-element="\&quot;true\&quot;" aria-multiline="\&quot;true\&quot;" data-placeholder="\&quot;Type">
<p class="\&quot;heading-style8\&quot;">Cargo liquefaction&nbsp;</p>
<p class="\&quot;heading-style9\&quot;">On board Test Procedures: Can Test</p>
<p>Check cargo condition before loading.</p>
<p>Carry out Can Test for cargoes which may liquefy as below:</p>
<ul id="\&quot;5a3b7e272317aa09aa141b58\&quot;" class="\&quot;ul-box" tabindex="\&quot;5a3b7e274787015461935d7c\&quot;" data-id="\&quot;NaN\&quot;">
<li>ï¿½\tFill a small can with sample cargo</li>
<li>ï¿½\tRepeatedly bang it on hard surface</li>
<li>ï¿½\tInspect the appearance of the material at the end of the test.</li>
<li>ï¿½\tArrange additional laboratory tests if free moisture or fluid condition appears</li>
</ul>
</div>
</div>
</td>
</tr>
</tbody>
</table>

<p class="\&quot;heading-style8\&quot;">Discharge Operations ï¿½ Monitoring and Execution</p>
<p>Keep hatch covers fully open during discharge operations, except where not permissible due to obstruction caused for the movement of shore gantries.</p>
<p>Discuss with stevedore to avoid banging of ship structure with bulldozers when dislodging cargo. Permit stevedores to use high pressure water jets only while sufficient cargo remains in the hold to absorb the water residue.</p>
<p>Attempt to have damages to ship structure repaired by stevedores before departure.</p>
<p>Calculate cargo quantity from draft survey and compare with shore figure at intervals not exceeding 6 hours and on changeover of grades.</p>
<p>Instruct stevedores to remove cargo spilled on deck during discharging.</p>
</div>

<p><span class="\&quot;heading-style8">Completion of Discharge</span></p>
<p>Inspect cargo holds for damage when all discharging equipment has been removed, if possible during daylight hours.</p>
<p>Check the bilges of the ballast holds on commencement of ballasting to ensure no leaks. Blank the bilge line of the ballast hold if any leak found. <td>
<table class="\&quot;draggable-item" border="\&quot;0\&quot;" width="\&quot;600\&quot;" cellspacing="\&quot;0\&quot;" cellpadding="\&quot;0\&quot;" align="\&quot;center\&quot;">
<tbody>
<tr>
<td class="\&quot;rLvE\&quot;">
<div class="\&quot;templateSettings\&quot;">&nbsp;</div>
<div class="\&quot;drg-rmv-settings-copy\&quot;">&nbsp;</div>
<div class="\&quot;text-resizer">
<div class="\&quot;ui-widget-text" role="\&quot;textbox\&quot;" contenteditable="\&quot;true\&quot;" spellcheck="\&quot;true\&quot;" data-medium-editor-element="\&quot;true\&quot;" aria-multiline="\&quot;true\&quot;">
<p>The Master must keep the following in mind before signing Bills of Lading:</p>
<ul id="\&quot;5a3b74e8ccf8a0f278572865\&quot;" class="\&quot;ul-box" tabindex="\&quot;5a3b74e83e6739f864b14bab\&quot;" data-id="\&quot;NaN\&quot;">
<li>B/L must only be signed as mentioned in voyage orders, and in favour of the parties, stated in the voyage orders.</li>
<li>Accuracy with respect to cargo description, figures and dates is essential.</li>
<li>The B/L must contain a standard disclaimer such as ï¿½Said to beï¿½ and/or ï¿½Quality, quantity, weight and value unknownï¿½ where describing the cargo.</li>
<li>Freight prepaid B/L should only be signed if owners have agreed to same</li>
<li>For time chartered ships Masters must not sign B/L which are ï¿½manifestly inconsistentï¿½ with the terms of the C/P, for example discharge port declared which is outside the range permitted by the Charter party</li>
<li>Owners and charterers requirements and formats will be nearly the same incorporating the relevant clauses.</li>
</ul>
<p>The Master may authorise the agents to sign the B/L on his behalf only when:</p>
<ul id="\&quot;5a3b74ecf5e89933af022f78\&quot;" class="\&quot;ul-box" tabindex="\&quot;5a3b74ec413915d098325f15\&quot;" data-id="\&quot;NaN\&quot;">
<li>This authority is given subject to strict conformity with Mateï¿½s receipt and charter party / voyage instructions.</li>
<li>The prescribed format is used</li>
<li>Agents who sign the B/L must send a fax copy to the ship. Master must compare this copy with the original B/L he receives in the discharging port</li>
</ul>
</div>
</div>
</td>
</tr>
</tbody>
</table>
</td>
</tr>

<div class="\&quot;text-resizer">
<div class="\&quot;ui-widget-text" role="\&quot;textbox\&quot;" contenteditable="\&quot;true\&quot;" spellcheck="\&quot;true\&quot;" data-medium-editor-element="\&quot;true\&quot;" aria-multiline="\&quot;true\&quot;">
<p>Deliver cargo only on production of original B/L. Check with agents well before arrival at discharging port to confirm that the B/L will be presented on arrival. Deliver cargo against Letters of Indemnity (LOI) only after approval of owners and not of charterers.</p>
<p>Mark original B/L when received on board at discharge port as ï¿½Accomplishedï¿½ and ï¿½all cargo discharged on date ________ï¿½ across the page, and retain it in the Masterï¿½s file.</p>
</div>

<p class="\&quot;heading-style8\&quot;">Lifting appliances and cargo gear</p>
<p>Ensure all loads are lifted vertically and never pulled at the slant.</p>
<p>Refer to the makerï¿½s manuals for crane operations.</p>
<p>Safety Devices are fitted to prevent operation outside of design limits, including:</p>
<ul id="\&quot;5a3b7370d29407faa43d6257\&quot;" class="\&quot;ul-box" tabindex="\&quot;5a3b7370228b4de734fc9afc\&quot;" data-id="\&quot;NaN\&quot;">
<li>Limit switches to stop the crane if it is attempted to be used above its upper hoisting limit or if it is attempted to lower the jib below the lower luffing limit.</li>
<li>Slack wire detectors to prevent wires from coming off the blocks.</li>
</ul>
<p>Reset all safety devices whenever wires are replaced.</p>
<p>Operate cranes for cargo operations by crew only if permitted by local authorities. Obtain chartererï¿½s letter of indemnity before any operation.</p>

<table class="\&quot;draggable-item" border="\&quot;0\&quot;" width="\&quot;600\&quot;" cellspacing="\&quot;0\&quot;" cellpadding="\&quot;0\&quot;" align="\&quot;center\&quot;">

<tr>
<td class="\&quot;rLvE\&quot;">
<div class="\&quot;templateSettings\&quot;">&nbsp;</div>

<div class="\&quot;text-resizer">
<div class="\&quot;ui-widget-text" role="\&quot;textbox\&quot;" contenteditable="\&quot;true\&quot;" spellcheck="\&quot;true\&quot;" data-medium-editor-element="\&quot;true\&quot;" aria-multiline="\&quot;true\&quot;" data-placeholder="\&quot;Type">
<p><span class="\&quot;heading-style8">Record keeping</span></p>
<p><span class="\&quot;heading-style9">Loading Computer Test Records</span></p>
<p>Verify accuracy of loading computer calculations with standard loading conditions given in the approved loading manual. Maintain signed records of the loading computer test. Enter the test data physically for each tank and cargo hold into the computer and verify the result.</p>
<p>Re-install the loading computer program in case large discrepancies are found. Carry out manual calculations and inform the Marine Superintendent in case re-installing fails.</p>
<p><span class="\&quot;heading-style9">Port Log Book</span></p>
<p>Record details of port operations including but not limited to:</p>
<ul id="\&quot;5a3b710a12a2bca67c6fce0a\&quot;" class="\&quot;ul-box" tabindex="\&quot;5a3b710a61bc000c111f83f5\&quot;" data-id="\&quot;NaN\&quot;">
<li>Commencement and completion times of cargo operations at each hold</li>
<li>State of weather, and any interruptions to cargo operations caused by weather</li>
<li>Any interruption in cargo operations due to ship or shore with reason for the interruption</li>
<li>Use of ship or shore cargo gear including quantities handled</li>
<li>Details of ballast operations</li>
<li>Record of the drafts, cargo loaded / discharged, ballast quantities and stresses at the end of each watch</li>
<li>Hold inspections carried out, mentioning person who carried out the inspection, and result of same</li>
</ul>
<p>\t<span class="\&quot;heading-style9">Chief Officerï¿½s Order Book</span></p>
<p>Maintain instructions of the Chief Officer in this book, especially for periods when the Chief Officer is not present for any reason.</p>
